<!--
  Appendix: Argument Diagrams.
  Placeholder. Full content to be drafted later.
  See docs/PROJECT_PLAN.md §18 and docs/DECISIONS.md D-027 for the
  appendix's planned scope, contents, and rationale.
-->
<appendix xml:id="appendix-diagramming">

  <title>Argument Diagrams</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      <em>This appendix is in preparation.</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      It will describe the optional visual conventions for diagramming
      argument structure — single arrows from premises to conclusions,
      brackets for dependent premises, separate arrows for independent
      support, divergent arguments where one premise supports more than
      one conclusion, and the convergent-layered composition — and will
      present worked diagrams of several arguments students have already
      met in the body of the book. Each diagram will be paired with the
      verbal reconstruction it represents.
    </p>
    <p>
      The verbal reconstruction is the primary form. Diagrams are an
      alternate visual representation that does not add information
      beyond what the reconstruction already conveys. Nothing in the
      assessments depends on producing or reading a diagram.
    </p>
    <p>
      Until this appendix is drafted, students who would benefit from
      visual representations can draw their own diagrams from the
      verbal reconstructions in Chapter 2.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <!--
    PLANNED CONTENTS (per PROJECT_PLAN.md §18):
    1. Frame: optional, accessibility-first, what diagrams add and don't add.
    2. The four conventions: single arrow; bracket for dependent;
       separate arrows for independent; divergent (one premise → many
       conclusions). Plus the convergent-layered composition as a
       consequence of the four applied together.
    3. Worked diagrams of arguments students have already met:
       - Library example (§1.3)
       - Modus tollens for God's existence (§1.3)
       - Modus ponens against God's existence (§1.3)
       - Running shoes (§1.4)
       - Oxfam (§1.4) — shows layered + dependent + independent + sub-conclusions
       - Food pantry (§2.4)
    4. A worked example of a divergent argument (newly written for this appendix).
    5. Accessibility statement up front and at the bottom.
    6. Optional exercises (no required solutions; exploratory).

    Implementation: each diagram is a <figure>+<image> with an
    embedded <description> giving the support structure in words for
    screen-reader users. Source for the diagrams in TikZ or PreTeXt's
    <diagram> element; SVG output for both PDF and HTML.
  -->

</appendix>
